726780f-a.text:
Grand Avenue, south side, between 79th Street and the New York Connecting Railroad. Eugene L. Armbruster states this house was erected in 189O by Christian Homeyer who sold it to the Brooklyn Union Gas Co. in 1915. However it has been the home of C. Ulrick in May 1890.
July 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726781f-a.text:
Grand Avenue, north side, west from 79th Street. The house seen in the foreground was a part of Washington Park. It does not appear inn the 1929 Queens Atlas. The New York connecting railroad extends through the site. The building in the background which was used as a dance hall is now occupied by Henry Klein and Co. Inc.
July 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726782f-a.text:
Grand Avenue, north side, west from 82nd Street (formerly Corinth Avenue) to 79th Street (formerly Ankener Street) showing two views of two old houses. In the background beyond house seen in the foreground of view No. 1 is the Seitz Park (Washington Park) Dance Hall. Views 1 and 2 show the C.F. Howard house (1873-1891). It lies directly in the 79th Street
line.
Ju1y 1923
Views l and 2
Eugene L Armbruster Collection
